Smart enumerations are a type of enumeration in Domain-Driven Design (DDD) that encapsulate behavior and logic. They are useful when you have a set of values that have associated behavior or rules.

Here's an example of a smart enumeration in C#:

```csharp
public enum OrderStatus
{
    New = 1,
    InProgress = 2,
    Shipped = 3,
    Delivered = 4,
    Cancelled = 5
}

public class OrderStatusExtensions
{
    public static bool IsNew(this OrderStatus status)
    {
        return status == OrderStatus.New;
    }

    public static bool IsShippedOrDelivered(this OrderStatus status)
    {
        return status == OrderStatus.Shipped || status == OrderStatus.Delivered;
    }

    public static bool CanBeCancelled(this OrderStatus status)
    {
        return status == OrderStatus.New || status == OrderStatus.InProgress;
    }
}
```

In this example, we've created an `OrderStatus` enumeration with a set of values. We've then created a static class `OrderStatusExtensions` with methods that operate on the `OrderStatus` values. These methods encapsulate the logic and behavior associated with each status.

